  <h2 id="why-plan">Why a Structured Plan Matters</h2>
  <p>
    A 2023 systematic review of more than 1,300 athletes (PMCID: <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11379499/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PMC11379499</a>) found that following a progressive, criteria-based protocol was the <strong>single biggest predictor</strong> of timely, complication-free return to sport <sup>1</sup>. Patients who tried to "wing it" experienced a 3-fold higher re-rupture rate and were 8 weeks slower to resume competition.
  </p>

  <h2 id="milestones">Key Milestones (Evidence-Based)</h2>
  <figure>
    <img src={milestonesImg.src} alt="Timeline graphic of rehab milestones" />
    <figcaption class="text-gray-500 text-sm">Typical progression adapted from PMC11379499 systematic review</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Weeks 0-2:</strong> Boot in full equinus, partial weight-bearing as tolerated.</li>
    <li><strong>Weeks 2-6:</strong> Gradual heel-wedge reduction ➝ full weight-bearing. Begin seated calf-activation &amp; isometrics.</li>
    <li><strong>Weeks 6-12:</strong> Transition out of boot. Double → single-leg heel raises. Stationary bike → light jog (~10-12 wk).</li>
    <li><strong>Months 3-6:</strong> Plyometrics, sport-specific drills, on-field running progression.</li>
    <li><strong>Month 6+:</strong> Return to unrestricted sport once strength ≥ 90 % of contralateral side &amp; hop tests symmetric <sup>2</sup>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="strength">Calf-Strength Targets</h2>
  <figure>
    <img src={calfStrengthImg.src} alt="Calf strength recovery chart" />
    <figcaption class="text-gray-500 text-sm">Average plantar-flexion strength recovery (isokinetic dynamometry) reported across 9 cohorts <sup>1</sup>.</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <p>
    The review highlights a <strong>rapid early gain</strong> once loading begins, followed by a plateau after 6 months. Continued heavy resistance (e.g. weighted heel raises, sled pushes) is essential beyond this point.
  </p>

